wan’s later works are more overtly political, more humane, and more ostentatiously literary than the early work, Dominic Head uncovers the continuity as well as the sense of evolution through the oeuvre. Head makes the case for McEwan’s prominence - pre-eminence, even - in the canon of contemporary British novelists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBritish novelists.  aIan McEwan.  abestseller lists.  aethical worldview.  agender relations.  ainnocence.  amale violence.  anarrative fiction.  arationality.  avested interests.1 aHead, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779173340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847791733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847791733/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles